courses.course_syllabus:
* Basic algebra (including rationalization, inequality, quadratic function, absolute value, index laws and logarithm, arithmetic progression, geometric progression);
* Mathematical Induction;
* Binomial Theorem;
* Notion of functions (including set notations, composition of functions, inverse function);
* Polynomials (including factorization, and graphs of polynomials);
* Exponential function and logarithmic functions;
* Trigonometric functions (including radian measure, compound angle formulae, inverse trigonometric functions);
* Limits of functions (including one-sided limits for function, limit at infinity for functions, notions of asymptotes and continuity for functions, special limits concerned with the exponential function, the logarithmic functions, and the trigonometric functions);
* Rudiments of one-variable differential calculus (including finding first derivative from first principle, basic rules of differentiation, chain rule, derivatives for the exponential function, the logarithmic function, and the trigonometric functions, higher-order derivatives);
* Rudiments of one-variable integral calculus (including indefinite integrals and definite integrals, simple methods of substitution, integration by parts, fundamental theorem of calculus).

* Basic ideas of limits of infinite sequences (including the definition of the Euler number *e* through infinite sequences);
* Limits and continuity of functions of one real variable (including Intermediate Value Theorem, bisection method, Extreme Value Theorem);
* One variable differential calculus and its applications (including the definition of the first derivative, implicit differentiation, Leibniz Rule, linearization, Newton’s method, Mean Value Theorem, monotonicity and convexity of functions, First and Second Derivative Test, the use of differentiation in verifying inequalities, rate of change, l’Hopital’s Rule, Taylor’s polynomials and Taylor’s series);
* One variable integral calculus and its applications (including method of computation of simple indefinite integrals of trigonometric, rational and irrational functions, reduction formula, Riemann sum, Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, application of definite integrals in evaluating limits, inequalities involving definite integrals, approximations of definite integrals by trapezoidal rule, Simpson’s rule, and Monte Carlo integration);
* Rudiments of first-order ordinary differential equations and their applications (including first-order linear equations, method of separation of variables, method of integrating factor, Euler’s method of approximation);
* Elementary linear algebra (including vectors in R^2 and R^3, matrices and determinants, systems of linear equations).

courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of the course, students should be able to
- Perform essential calculations in matrices, determinants, and linear systems;
- Use these calculations in the context of certain business and scientific applications;
- Realize the importance of linear algebra in a broad spectrum of subject areas;
- Prepare for undergraduate studies requiring statistical knowledge.

