We introduce the students to the some basic concepts of abstract algebra and get a flavor of the modern theoretical mathematics, and enable them to produce rigorous mathematical proofs based on abstract theory on their own. Upon completion of the course, students should be able to
- learn the basics of group theory: normal subgroups, quotient groups, direct products, structure of finitely generated abelian groups, group action, Cayley's theorem, Sylow theorems;
- learn the basics of ring theory: prime and maximal ideals, polynomial rings, factorization in integral domains, principal ideal domains, unique factorization domains;
- apply basic results and techniques to solve problems in the theory and other related subjects;
- prepare for further studies in algebra-related subjects.

We introduce the students to the advanced level of abstract algebra so that they are able to appreciate the exciting development of abstract algebra since the mid 19th century. And we provide the students with a solid background to understand deep mathematics and make them well-prepared for more advanced topics like: number theory, representation theory, algebraic geometry. Upon completion of the course, students should be able to
- learn the basics of field extension: algebraic extensions, algebraic closures, geometric constructions, finite fields;
- learn the basics of Galois theory: splitting fields, separable and inseparable extensions, Galois extensions, Galois correspondences, cyclotomic extensions, solvability by radicals;
- apply basic results and techniques to solve problems in the theory and other related subjects;
- prepare for graduate studies in algebra-related subjects such as algebraic geometry, algebraic number theory and representation theory.

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to
- develop a theoretical understanding in fundamental concept and approach of Operations research appropriate to the further study;
- formulate a real-world problem as an appropriate mathematical programming model;
- implement algorithms/methods of operations research in solving problems on mathematical programming;
- critically analyse and interpret results on the practical level.

Students are expected to learn the basic optimization theory and concepts with emphasis on their mathematical aspects. Upon completion of the course, students are expected to:

1. learn the basic mathematical concepts and techniques for optimization;
2. be aware of the important role of mathematics in optimization;
3. appreciate the importance of optimization theory in the real world;
4. learn how to design optimization models for real-world problems;
5. implement algorithms/methods in solving problems on optimization.

